commit_message: first commit

First draft of a new, fast dependency JSR-330 injector.This injector is roughly based on MiniGuice:nhttp://code.google.com/p/google-guice/source/browse/extensions/mini/src/com/google/inject/mini/MiniGuice.javannUnlike Guice, this injector uses only static configuration.nThis will enable more up front checking as well as backendsnthat use code generation instead of reflection.nnCurrent limitations:n - no support for circular dependencies.n - no method injection.n
Address pom.xml problems
Address code review comments from bob@ and edenman@
Rename Linker.getBinding() to Linker.requestBinding().
More code review comments addressed.
Merge pull request #1 from square/firstdraftFirst draft of a fast new JSR-330 dependency injector.
New, very basic Java code generator.The code generator is only concerned with the high levelnconstructs; it relies on the caller to worry about makingnsure the actual statements are well formed.n

Use Strings for Keys.Strings will be a little less type safe, but they're goingnto be a lot easier to use with code generation. Otherwisenwe'd need to implement all of the various 'Type' interfacesnand do hacks to guarantee equals and hashCode compatibilitynwith the built-in implementations.n

First draft of the @Provides processor.Given input like this:nnpackage com.squareup;nnimport com.squareup.injector.Provides;nimport javax.inject.Named;nnpublic class Hello {n  @Provides @Named(foo) String provideString(@Named(bar) Integer i) {nreturn foo;n  }n}nnThis will generate a class like this:nnpackage com.squareup;nimport com.squareup.injector.internal.Binding;nimport com.squareup.injector.internal.ModuleAdapter;nimport java.util.Map;nimport com.squareup.injector.internal.Linker;npublic final class Hello$ModuleAdapternimplements ModuleAdapter<Hello> {n  @Overriden  public Map<String, Binding<?>> getBindings(Hello module) {njava.util.Map<java.lang.String, com.squareup.injector.internal.Binding<?>> result = new java.util.HashMap<java.lang.String, com.squareup.injector.internal.Binding<?>>();nresult.put(@javax.inject.Named(value=foo)/java.lang.String, new provideStringBinding(module));nreturn result;n  }n  private static class provideStringBindingn  extends Binding<String> {nprivate final Hello module;nprivate Binding<Integer> p0;npublic provideStringBinding(Hello module) {n  super(com.squareup.Hello.class, @javax.inject.Named(value=foo)/java.lang.String);n  this.module = module;n}n@Overridenpublic void attach(Linker linker) {n  p0 = (com.squareup.injector.internal.Binding<java.lang.Integer>) linker.requestBinding(@javax.inject.Named(value=bar)/java.lang.Integer, com.squareup.Hello.class);n}n@Overridenpublic String get() {n  return module.provideString(p0.get());n}n@Overridenpublic boolean isSingleton() {n  return true;n}n  }n}n

First draft of the @Inject processor.Given input like this:nnpackage com.squareup;nnimport javax.inject.Inject;nimport javax.inject.Named;nnpublic class World {n  @Inject @Named(bar) String bar;n  @Inject World(@Named(foo) Integer foo) {n  }n}nnThis will generate a class like this:nnpackage com.squareup;nimport com.squareup.injector.internal.Binding;nimport com.squareup.injector.internal.Linker;nfinal class World$InjectAdapternextends Binding<World> {n  private Binding<Integer> c0;n  private Binding<String> f0;n  public World$InjectAdapter() {nsuper(com.squareup.World.class, com.squareup.World);n  }n  @Overriden  public void attach(Linker linker) {nc0 = (com.squareup.injector.internal.Binding<java.lang.Integer>) linker.requestBinding(@javax.inject.Named(value=foo)/java.lang.Integer, com.squareup.World.class);nf0 = (com.squareup.injector.internal.Binding<java.lang.String>) linker.requestBinding(@javax.inject.Named(value=bar)/java.lang.String, com.squareup.World.class);n  }n  @Overriden  public World get() {ncom.squareup.World result = new com.squareup.World(c0.get());ninjectMembers(result);nreturn result;n  }n  @Overriden  public void injectMembers(World object) {nobject.bar = f0.get();n  }n  @Overriden  public boolean isSingleton() {nreturn true;n  }n}n

New annotation-driven API that uses entry points.This is more dynamic than before because it's now possiblento keep the dependency graph around and reuse it to injectntypes on demand.nnThe alternative required a lot of boilerplate and failed tonpermit injectable types to be shared between injectors. Itnwas particularly problematic when an Android entry point (likenan Activity or Fragment) was shared by both an application andna test.n

Fix several problems with MembersInjectors.We were failing to identify types that supported members injectionnbut not construction. This splits bindings into two types: those thatncan be constructable and those that can't. It now fails early if youninject a MembersInjector<Foo> for Foo that isn't constructable.nnAlso rename DependencyGraph to ObjectGraph.n
Merge pull request #12 from square/jwilson/membersinjectorFix several problems with MembersInjectors.

Replace @Injector with @Module.Moving static injections and entry points to the module levelnwill increase modularity. I still need something like @Injectornso I can do full-program static analysis at build time.n
Merge pull request #14 from square/jwilson/atmoduleReplace @Injector with @Module.

Detect problems at runtime.This currently detects circular dependencies. In the mediumnterm I'd like to do most of those checks at build time usingnAPT.nnThe error checking is expensive and optional. You dont neednto call detectProblems() in production!n
Merge pull request #15 from square/jwilson/problemdetectorDetect problems at runtime.

Support lazy object graphs.This splits ObjectGraph into 2 modes:n - lazy mode is ideal for production. Only the bindings you need rightn   here and right now are constructed and satisfied.n - eager mode is ideal for development. All of the runtime errors aren   detected up front.nnNote that I'm not calling these PRODUCTION/DEVELOPMENT (as Guice did)nsince priorities may differ between server apps (slow startup doesn'tnmatter) and mobile apps (fast startup does matter).n
Merge pull request #16 from square/jwilson/lazySupport lazy object graphs.

Fix many injector bugs to run Square apps.This splits member and provider keys into two namespaces.nWe had a problem where an abstract class was bound usingnan @Provides method, and also needed member injection bynits subclass. This split allows both bindings to coexist.nnImplement singletons by looking for the @Singleton annotation.nnSupport Guice @Provides, necessary to bootstrap Squarenapps.n
Merge pull request #17 from square/jwilson/bugsFix many injector bugs to run Square apps.

Better failures on duplicate bindings.The previous code had two problems:n - if a duplicate binding existed, we'd ignore then   exception if it occurred in a generated class.n - if a duplicate binding existed, the second bindingn   would win.n

Optimize ObjectGraph.This includes two key optimizations:n - Use generated code for @Module. The ModuleAdapter interfacen   was formerly only used for generated code. With this changen   that type is an abstract class and its used for both codegenn   and reflection.n - Change AtInjectBinding to avoid reflection in attach(). Then   attach method is invoked multiple times so we shouldn't don   expensive work in it.nnOn one particular device this improved app start up from 4.1nseconds to 3.1 seconds.n

Documentation, style and small renaming changes.The only behavior change is to RuntimeAggregatingPlugin. This classnused to allow other plugins to return null if they couldn't resolvena value. If all plugins returned null, it would throw. The newnbehavior is to have child plugins throw, and to rethrow the lastnplugin's exception if necessary.nnThe upside of this change is that we emit better errors. In the newntwoAtInjectConstructorsIsRejected, we were printing this error:nn  No available @Inject handlers could be found for keyn  dagger.InjectionTest$TwoAtInjectConstructors in classn  dagger.InjectionTest$TwoAtInjectConstructors requiredn  by class dagger.InjectionTest$26TestModulennWith this change the error is better:nn  Too many injectable constructors onn  dagger.InjectionTest$TwoAtInjectConstructors requiredn  by class dagger.InjectionTest$26TestModulennAlso renaming 'augments' to 'addsTo' and ObjectGraph.extend()nto ObjectGraph.plus().nnAlso adding extensive documentation for Lazy.n

A few more changes to eliminate reflection.Presently ModuleAdapterProcessor generates members/foo.bar.Blah keys for non-interfaces present in the @Module(injects=...) list. This change, instead of simply saying if class, list a members key, lists the provision key and only generates the members key if the type has injectable fields. It short circuits that logic if the type is provided in an `@Provides` method in the same module, but doesn't short circuit if the type has no `@Inject` constructor, because it may have been provided up-stream by another included module or adds-to referenced module.nnIn short, if the processor can see the type, and can inspect it, and it has no field injection, no members/foo key will be listed in injects.  But also, if it KNOWS this type will be given through an @Provides method, it will also not list a members key.  This results in a lot less unintentional reflection since linkEverything -> linker.linkAll() will not then attempt to load `InjectAdapter`s for a lot of members keys that are actually already present as provides bindings.nnIn practice, this was discovered by large graphs with a lot of value types being inserted into the graph and being listed as injectable, forcing a lot of reflective bindings to be created that would never ever be used (since there was no members-injection).n
